<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-11</title>

<p><b>Opening synthesis.</b> The most active research thread in the past two weeks is not a new architecture, but a shift in what we ask world models and VLAs to do. Three papers stood out because they try to make deployment less expensive: GigaWorld-1 asks how a video world model can become a trustworthy <i>policy evaluator</i> instead of a demo generator; PhysisForcing shows that a small physics-aware fine-tuning loss can make a DiT world model respect object trajectories and contact relations without changing inference; and VLA-Corrector treats the fixed action chunk of a frozen VLA as a bug to be detected and truncated at runtime. In each case the key insight is about <i>action faithfulness</i> — staying aligned with what the robot actually does — rather than photorealism or raw accuracy. The code inspections and toy probes below support the mechanisms but also surface a shared limitation: the headline numbers still rest on unreleased benchmark harnesses or missing checkpoints.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> GigaWorld-1 is the clearest seed for a research thread. It reframes world-model evaluation from "does it look good?" to "does it rank policies the same way real robot rollouts do?" and backs the claim with the largest controlled study in this period (324k simulated rollouts paired with real executions).</p>
</callout>

<h1>World models as robot evaluators and simulators</h1>

<p>World models for robotics have been sold as data engines, policies, and interaction environments. The newest papers add a fourth role — evaluator — and argue that the design rules for the four roles are not the same. A model that generates beautiful video can still fail to predict whether a policy will succeed, and a model that tracks contact physics may still be too slow to train. The papers in this theme are asking how to specialize.</p>

