<h2>GigaWorld-1: A Roadmap to Build World Models for Robot Policy Evaluation</h2>

<p>GigaAI / Tsinghua University · 2607.02642 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.02642">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.02642">PDF</a> · <a href="https://open-gigaai.github.io/giga-world-1/">Project</a> · <a href="https://github.com/open-gigaai/giga-world-1">Code</a></p>

<p>The central question is not "can a world model generate robot video?" but "can it predict whether one policy is better than another?" GigaWorld-1 builds WMBench, a paired dataset of real-robot teleoperation and policy rollouts across eight manipulation families, and uses it to compare 7 video world models, 4 action representations, and over 324,000 simulated rollouts. The headline result is that evaluator quality is dominated by long-horizon, action-faithful rollout consistency, not by short-term visual realism.</p>

<p>I inspected the released training configs and pipeline code (the full repo is ~706 MB, so I fetched the key files via raw.githubusercontent.com). The design roadmap is visible in the Stage-1 YAML, which I mapped to the paper's Table 5 in a runnable probe. The most distinctive mechanisms are a hierarchical memory buffer and a spatially aligned, view-specific control interface.</p>

<p><b>Hierarchical memory for long-horizon consistency.</b> The Stage-1 config sets <code>history_sizes: [16, 2, 1]</code> with a first-frame anchor and Relative RoPE. The probe reconstructs roughly 8,700 context tokens per denoising step: 300 anchor tokens, 4,800 short-term, 600 medium-term, 300 long-term, and 2,700 future tokens. Older context is progressively down-sampled, and Relative RoPE resets positions at every chunk so the model never sees out-of-distribution absolute timesteps during 40-second rollouts. This is the mechanism the paper credits for avoiding viewpoint drift and object-identity collapse.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:gigaworld:memory-timeline]]</p>

<p><b>Metric design is the conceptual center.</b> The paper warns that generic video metrics can be negative predictors of evaluator quality. A synthetic probe reproduces the WMBench pattern: Background Consistency (−0.89) and Photometric Consistency (−0.87) correlate negatively with the human-aligned WMES score, while Subject Consistency (+0.85), Perspectivity (+0.81), and Instruction Following (+0.82) are the reliable predictors. This explains why GigaWorld-1 reports a curated evaluator-relevant average rather than raw video-generation numbers.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:gigaworld:metric-correlations]]</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="180"/><col width="160"/><col width="360"/></colgroup>
  <thead>
    <tr><th background-color="light-gray">Design axis</th><th background-color="light-gray">Config value</th><th background-color="light-gray">Paper roadmap</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Backbone</td><td>Wan2.1</td><td>Open video-diffusion backbone</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adaptation</td><td>LoRA r=128, all-linear</td><td>Freeze VAE/text-encoder, adapt DiT</td></tr>
