  </tbody>
</table>

<p><b>Caveats.</b> The WMBench metric code and the Qwen3-VL LoRA WMES judge are not in the current public repo; the <code>videoalign/</code> directory contains a reward-model trainer, not the evaluator. The README also cites the earlier GigaWorld-0 arXiv ID (2511.19861) in its BibTeX. So the probes verify the architectural mechanisms, but the 14.9% improvement over baselines and the 324k-rollout claim rest on the paper and the public challenge leaderboard, not on independently runnable code.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>PhysisForcing: Physics Reinforced World Simulator for Robotic Manipulation</h2>

<p>Peking University · 2606.28128 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.28128">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.28128">PDF</a> · <a href="https://dagroup-pku.github.io/PhysisForcing.github.io/">Project</a></p>

<p>PhysisForcing takes the opposite approach to GigaWorld-1: instead of building a new evaluation benchmark, it changes the training objective of a DiT-based video world model so that the model is penalized for physical inconsistency. The claim is that most manipulation failures are local (discontinuous trajectories) or relational (broken contact), and that a pair of auxiliary losses on a single middle DiT block can fix them without adding inference cost.</p>

<p>The method has three steps. First, a physics mask is extracted from the ground-truth clip with CoTracker3 and Depth-Anything-V2. Second, two losses are added to the standard flow-matching objective on the hidden features of a middle DiT block:</p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{FM}} + \lambda_{\mathrm{pix}} \mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{phy}}_{\mathrm{pix}} + \lambda_{\mathrm{sem}} \mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{phy}}_{\mathrm{sem}}</latex></p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{phy}}_{\mathrm{pix}}</latex> supervises per-point trajectories via soft-argmax inside the mask, and <latex>\mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{phy}}_{\mathrm{sem}}</latex> matches the pairwise token-relation matrix inside the mask to a frozen V-JEPA 2 encoder. Both auxiliary models are discarded at inference, so the released PF-Wan bundle is a standard Wan2.2 pipeline with a tuned checkpoint.</p>

<p>Because the training code is listed as "Coming soon," I built a pure-NumPy diagnostic that reproduces the mask extraction and both losses on a synthetic moving-square video. A tiny linear student is trained under four loss combinations. The pattern matches the paper's ablation: the pixel loss strongly reduces trajectory error, the semantic loss strongly reduces relation error, and the combined loss balances both.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:physisforcing:metric-curves]]</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="200"/><col width="160"/><col width="160"/><col width="160"/></colgroup>
  <thead>
    <tr><th background-color="light-gray">Training variant</th><th background-color="light-gray">Clean MSE</th><th background-color="light-gray">Trajectory error</th><th background-color="light-gray">Relation error</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>MSE only</td><td>0.024</td><td>69.79</td><td>0.014</td></tr>
    <tr><td>MSE + pixel</td><td>3.896</td><td>21.97</td><td>0.134</td></tr>
    <tr><td>MSE + semantic</td><td>0.025</td><td>77.42</td><td>0.008</td></tr>
    <tr><td>MSE + pixel + semantic</td><td>1.902</td><td>19.45</td><td>0.072</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><b>Interpretation.</b> The toy probe confirms that the two losses pull features in orthogonal, complementary directions. It does not reproduce the reported +22.3% R-Bench lift, but it makes the mechanism concrete and explains why the largest gains appear on physical-semantic domain scores rather than on pure visual-quality scores.</p>

<h1>VLA inference-time adaptation</h1>

<p>While world-model papers try to make simulation cheaper, VLA papers are trying to make a frozen policy safer to deploy. The common theme is moving intelligence from training time to test time: instead of retraining the whole model for a new environment, add a small external module that watches execution and intervenes.</p>

