<h2>VLA-Corrector: Lightweight Detect-and-Correct Inference for Adaptive Action Horizon</h2>

<p>Zhejiang University OmniAI · 2607.01804 · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.01804">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.01804">PDF</a> · <a href="https://zju-omniai.github.io/vla-corrector/">Project</a> · <a href="https://github.com/ZJU-OmniAI/vla-corrector">Code</a></p>

<p>VLA-Corrector attacks the fixed action-horizon problem of action-chunked VLAs. Most generative policies predict a chunk of future actions and execute them open-loop. In contact-rich tasks, small perturbations amplify inside the blind spot. VLA-Corrector keeps the base VLA frozen and adds a small latent-dynamics corrector that watches visual features and decides when the queued actions have gone stale.</p>

<p>The loop has four pieces:</p>
<ol>
  <li seq="auto"><b>External corrector</b> <latex>M_\phi</latex>: a ~40 M-parameter residual MLP trained on frozen VLA visual features to predict the short-horizon latent residual <latex>\Delta Z = Z_{t+k} - Z_t</latex> induced by the action.</li>
  <li seq="auto"><b>Latent-space Vision Monitor (LVM)</b>: compares predicted and observed residuals using <latex>E_t = 1 - \mathrm{CosSim}(\Delta Z^{\mathrm{pred}}, \Delta Z^{\mathrm{real}})</latex>.</li>
  <li seq="auto"><b>Event-triggered truncation</b>: when <latex>E_t</latex> exceeds a robust threshold for <latex>p</latex> consecutive steps, discard the remaining queued actions and replan.</li>
  <li seq="auto"><b>Online Gradient Guidance (OGG)</b>: on the recovery replan, backprop through the corrector to nudge the first action so its predicted latent effect aligns with the desired correction.</li>
</ol>

<p>The reported MetaWorld results on π₀.₅ are baseline 48.70%, +Truncation 60.35%, +Truncation+OGG 64.35%. I could not run the official stack because the repo ships no checkpoints or datasets and requires a LeRobot fork plus MuJoCo/MetaWorld/LIBERO. Instead I pulled the source files through the GitHub API and built a pure-NumPy probe of a 2-D point-mass tracker with a tiny latent-dynamics corrector.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:vlacorrector:probe-metrics]]</p>

<table>
  <colgroup><col width="220"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/><col width="120"/></colgroup>
  <thead>
    <tr><th background-color="light-gray">Method</th><th background-color="light-gray">Success rate</th><th background-color="light-gray">Policy calls</th><th background-color="light-gray">Success / call</th><th background-color="light-gray">Truncations</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Baseline H=5</td><td>39.5%</td><td>16.00</td><td>0.025</td><td>0.00</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Baseline H=20</td><td>25.5%</td><td>4.00</td><td>0.064</td><td>0.00</td></tr>
    <tr><td>+ Truncation (H=20)</td><td>35.5%</td><td>4.98</td><td>0.071</td><td>1.18</td></tr>
    <tr><td>+ Truncation + OGG (H=20)</td><td>33.5%</td><td>5.03</td><td>0.067</td><td>1.24</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><b>What the probe shows.</b> Truncation recovers most of the closed-loop benefit while keeping policy-call count near the long-horizon baseline. OGG's additional gain is small in this toy setting, mirroring the paper's ablation where truncation alone closes most of the gap. The toy corrector has ~12k parameters and ~25k FLOPs per forward pass, confirming the "lightweight" shape even if the real scale is larger.</p>

<p><b>Code-paper discrepancies.</b> The released evaluation script is more complex than the paper describes. It uses an EWMA-smoothed inconsistency score, a bootstrap phase, a base noise floor, a jump trigger, a hard-retrigger margin, and separate on/off thresholds — none of which appear in the concise median+MAD description. It is unclear how much of the reported gain comes from the core idea versus these extra heuristics.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p><b>Evaluation is becoming the product.</b> GigaWorld-1, RoboDojo, and the Imagined Rollouts diagnosis all treat evaluation as a first-class research object. The community is no longer satisfied with a world model that looks good; it wants a cheap, consistent signal that predicts real-robot outcomes. This is a healthy shift, but it also means the field needs standardized harnesses and released metric code — which are still missing.</p>

<p><b>Action faithfulness is the new visual realism.</b> PhysisForcing, GigaWorld-1, and VLA-Corrector all optimize for staying aligned with executed actions rather than for photorealism or next-token accuracy. The metric probes in GigaWorld-1 and the toy diagnostic in PhysisForcing both show that improving physical consistency can hurt conventional video-quality metrics.</p>

<p><b>Partial releases are the norm.</b> All three deep-dived papers publish code, but none publish the full stack needed to reproduce the headline numbers: GigaWorld-1 lacks WMBench metric code and the WMES judge; PhysisForcing lists training code as "Coming soon"; VLA-Corrector ships no checkpoints or datasets. The mechanisms are inspectable, but the empirical claims rest on the paper tables.</p>
